body.plain:
Fenne Lilly told about the meaning of the song in an interview:
“It’s not a song about heartbreak in the usual sense of the word; it’s more a sense of losing what I held close and not understanding how I felt about people moving on and changing, especially myself.”

annotations:
Sleeping top to toe with me
 Isn’t what it used to be

Fenne acknowledges the coming-to-an-end of the relationship and the hollowness of said feeling.

In the lines:

“Sleeping top to toe with me
Isn’t what it used to be”

Fenne addresses how the nearing end of their relationship approaches, the more a level of uneasiness and disassociation washes over them.

Tell me it’s the best for us
 Take away the truth because

The narrator doesn’t believe the end of their relationship is the best thing for them, and tells her ex-lover to “take away the truth” (lie) about how breaking up is “the best for [them],” in order to feel less hurt.

Won’t you take me to your bed
 I should have said
 I need you more
She still ends up blaming herself for the breakup

Please don’t go, I need you
 Take control, you tell me
 Please don’t go, I need you
 Take control
It’s almost ironic – the whole song Fenne states how her partner is controlling her but she now needs this sense of controlling to feel like he still wants to be with her

And you tell me I’m a child
 And take my light
 To smoke your mind

She finds her partner being condescending to her, and gas lighting her. Almost literally using this ‘gas lighting’ to metaphorically smoke and relax his mind.

An alternative way to interpret this is that her partner takes her hopefulness for the relationship and tells her she’s being unrealistic to make themself feel better.

So, I’m changing all my days
 To make your nights
Fenne finds herself changing herself for her partner, inconveniencing herself.
Feelings always change like this

At her Southampton album release show, Fenne said that she was always the person being ‘dumped’ rather than ‘dumping’. This implies the end of a relationship, and the fear which goes alongside such.

Fenne revealed she wrote this song when she was fifteen.

description.plain:
In the world of her music, Fenne’s inveterate vulnerability transforms what-ifs into worse case scenarios, hypotheticals into heartache. This heart-on-sleeve ethos spawned her early songwriting and colored the emotional intensity of her already confessional work. Now, she’s facing this tendency towards emergency head on.

annotations: We’re all sick of waiting for a moment to stop and sleep it off
Lily identifies this as a feeling felt collectively. She isn’t alone feeling this way, but is tired of doing so.
So leave it out
This continues the idea of having control over your thoughts – she doesn’t need to think about these things that are causing her anxiety.

These conversations I have with myself
 Only as hard as I make them
 These complications I have with my health
 Only go as far as I take them

Fenne Lily makes it clear that she knows she has control of her thoughts. She has the ability to choose the subject she thinks about. Lily contrasts these with the idea of being a hypochondriac: a person who is abnormally anxious about their health and self-diagnoses themself with illness.
In an interview with stereogum, she says the song is “addressing myself as both the cause of and solution to my anxieties”.

description.plain:
‘Berlin’ is the second single released on Fenne Lily’s sophomore album BREACH. Its minimal lyrics contain fragments and recollections of the month the writer spent in Berlin, learning how to be alone.

Peaceful guitar riffs make up a careful melody that reflects the budding self-acceptance and resolve by the songwriter.

Fenne composes the song out of her memories of the voice notes made during that month, lost via an accident with her phone on the returning plane ride. Her experiences in Berlin include reading Patti Smith’s book Just Kids multiple times and a solo venture into the techno sanctuary Berghain.

annotations: But it hurts to feel this much

In an interview with Dork, Fenne said:

“When I started writing I had my first boyfriend and was struggling to deal with the fact that I wasn’t overly comfortable with going to parties and being a teenager; that I was anxious and I didn’t really know that was okay. At that time I was like, ‘I’m a freak, all I want to do is cry…‘”

Her experience of emotional intensity and social anxiety suggests she’s a highly sensitive person.
’Cause I’ve grown to need this pain

Fenne Lily seems to be describing an experience of codependence, in which an unhealthy relationship is maintained because the subject feels they need their partner, and need to take care of them, even in the face of mounting pain and destruction.

annotations:
’Cause I need this more than I knew
 More than I’d like, more than you do
In retrospect, Fenne now realises that she realises that she needed her ex-lover more than she thought she did while she was in the relationship.

Finding this is hard
 Fighting this is new

I know this is a stretch, but this song always reminded me of a bi girl having her first crush on a girl. These two lines read, at least to me, as someone who is only just having to come to terms with their feelings for someone they wouldn’t expect to have romantic interest in.

And I know what I want
 But I know what I’ll lose
Fenne lulls about how much she loves her partner and expresses her longing for their relationship but inevitably succumbs to her fear of losing her lover

annotations:
I wonder if you saw that I was sorry for the beating of my heart
 When it woke you in the car park

Fenne is over-aware of the noises her body is making – even the beating of her own heart, a sound she cannot deafen. She feels the need to apologise to the person, taking the blame for waking them, showing that she is desperately trying to make the other person comfortable, even if it inconveniences her.
